	<h1>The World Wide Web</h1>
		<!--I feel like I'm overusing the paragraph tags but it seems necessary to separate sections, please let me know if there's a better method I'm missing-->
	<p>
	<b>HTML:</b> HyperText Markup Language is the document that the majority of the web is made up of, browsers interpret the HTML language to make it viewable.
	</p>
	
	<h1>Components of the Web</h1>

	<p>Client-->Browser-->Internet-->HTTP-->Servers</p>

	<img src="componentsoftheweb.png"width="200px" height="100px"alt="Components of the web">
	
	


	<h1>HTML Document Structure</h1>
	<p>Generally an indent means a new idea. The level increases at the beginning of the idea and decreases when finished.
		<p><b>HTML Document example:</b></p>
	

		<p>&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt; This just tells the interpreter that this is an HTML 5 document</p>
		<p>&lt;html&gt; this tag just opens our document</p>
		<p>&lt;head&gt;This is my Header that is not going to show on the page, but contains metadata or information that can be used by browsers and search engines
		&lt;/head&gt;</p>
		<p>&lt;title&gt; typically a short one line tag that is closed on the same line-shows on the browser tab&lt;/title&gt;</p>
		<p>&lt;body&gt; this is the content of the web page.</p>
			<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;h1&gt;Headers can be from level 1 (smallest) to level 6&lt;/h1&gt;</p>
			<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;p&gt; Paragraphs and headers are both child elements of the body and can be indented at the same level&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;/body&gt;</p>
		</p>

	<h1>Basic HTML Elements</h1> 
		<p>An opening and closing tag with some content in the middle</p>

	<p><b>Block-level Elements</b> start on a new line and takes up the full width (stretches out to the left and right as far as it can).

	<ul>Examples:
		<li>&lt;div&gt; is used as a container for other HTML elements. No required attributes for it, but usually used for style and class.  In CSS, div can style content blocks.</li>
		<li>&lt;h1&gt; - &lt;h6&gt;</li>
		<li>&lt;p&gt;text&lt;/p&gt; Defines a paragraph. The content of the &lt;p&gt; element is in a "box" 
		&lt;form&gt;</li>
	</ul>
	</p>

	<p><b>Inline Elements</b> donâ€™t start on a new line and only takes up as much width as needed

	<ul>Examples:
		<li>&lt;b&gt;text&lt;/b&gt;  bold </li>
		<li>&lt;em&gt;text&lt;/em&gt; italic</li>
		<li>&lt;br&gt; Creates a line break </li>
		<li>&lt;span&gt; is a container used for text elements.  No required attributes for it, but usually used for style and class.  In CSS, span can style text blocks.</li>
		<li>&lt;a&gt; Anchor</li>
		<li>&lt;strong&gt; strong text</li>
	</ul>
	</p>


	<h1>HTML Attributes</h1>
	<p>Some elements have attributes in their opening tags which give additional information to the browser

	<ul>Examples:
		<li>&lt;a href="url"&gt;website&lt;/a&gt; Creates a hyperlink to the href attribute value url and names it websites</li>
		<li>&lt;img src="url" alt="text"&gt; Displays the image hosted at the src attribute value "url" or local file. If the image cannot be displayed, then the alt attribute value "text" is shown.</li></p>
</body>


